Summaries

five sample summaries

[1] The speaker described the ability of humans to communicate complex thoughts through language, and then went on to show that there are about 7,000 different languages in the world, each with different sounds and structures. She provided specific examples, based on recent scientific research, to answer the age-old question, "Does language shape thought?" She explained that Kuuk Thaayorre, the language of the Australian Aborigines, does not use "left/right" but uses directions (north, south, east, west) to recognize space, allowing speakers to grasp orientation very accurately. This reveals that language influences spatial perception. It also showed that the sense of time also differs by language and culture, and that the way of thinking changes depending on whether it is body-centered or topography-centered. Also discussed were differences in arithmetic ability based on the presence or absence of number words, language differences in the representation of colors, and examples of how grammaticality (noun gender) affects thinking. Furthermore, the differences between English and Spanish in the representation of accidents showed how different languages have different objects of attention and memory focus, which can even affect judicial and social decisions. Finally, she concluded that language diversity demonstrates the diversity of human cognition and that how we "think" is shaped by language. On the other hand, she also emphasized that many languages are in danger of disappearing, and the resulting loss of cognitive diversity is problematic.
[2] There are 7000 languages in the world. The structures, sounds and so on differ in each language. She and her lab work to question the language we speak to shape the way we think. She gave us some examples. First, she introduced the ethnic group which does not use left and right. Instead they use directions, and also they use direction when they want to speak about the flow of time.Second, in some languages, every noun has grammatical gender, and it affects how people describe the thing. When the noun is grammatically feminine, people use feminine words to describe it. She thinks the beauty of linguistic diversity reveals to us how genius and flexible the human mind is. She is worried about losing a lot of languages.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       
[3]                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                             
[4] Speaking languages are magical abilities that we humans have. Our voice makes the air vibrate and go to your eardrum. Then, transform that into thoughts. Thats why we can share our thoughts or ideas across our minds. There are about 7000 languages spoken around the world. Does the language we speak shape the way we think? Ancient people said to have a second language is to have a second soul. On the other hand, Shakespeare thinks that language doesont craft reality. These arguments go back and forth for thousands of years. There are a lot of different languages. Some people dont use left and right or numbers. People make lots of kinds of expressions. Languages are also visually active. Plus, sometimes words are named by feminine or male meanings so people think about the words such as beautiful and elegant and if it is male like words, they think strong or long. Human mind is actually narrow and biased.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
[5] There are about 7000 languages spoken around the world, and all of them differ in sounds, vocabularies, and structures. This leads to a big question: Does the language we speak shape the way we think? This is an ancient question. Charlemagne once said, To have a second language is to have a second soul, suggesting that language crafts reality. On the other hand, Shakespeares Juliet says, Whats in a name? A rose by any other name would smell as sweet, implying language may not shape reality. Some countries use north, south, east, and west instead of left and right. Others dont have words for numbers or for dark and light colors. Languages also use different adjectives for masculine and feminine nouns. For example, in German, people may describe bridges as beautiful and elegant, while in Spanish, they might say strong and long. These differences show that speakers of different languages have different ideas. But its not just about others  its about you. Your language shapes your thoughts, so ask yourself,why do I think the way I do?

[1] It is difficult to think about things that are not obvious. I have some questions about whether Australian Aborigines use the relationship between sun and shadow, or whether they judge by the visual information of the place where they live when they want to know the direction. If it is the latter, I thought that they might lose their sense of direction if they went to a place they had never seen before. From the example of the penguins, I also wondered if there is a way to count the number of things, they use the unity of quantity or they do not think about the number complementary.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            
[2] In this video, I learned that there are various nuances in describing one substance depending on the country. I thought that different people have different ways of distinguishing between the same colors, and different ways of expressing the language of a single bridge. I am a Korean resident in Japan, but since I was raised in Japan, I thought I was similar to Japanese people                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              
[3] I found this TED Talk fascinating because it opened my eyes to the deep connection between language and thought. Before watching it, I had never seriously considered that the language I speak could shape how I perceive time, space, or even objects around me. The examples of how German and Spanish speakers might think differently about a bridge simply because of grammatical gender were especially intriguing. It made me realize that language does more than convey information; it influences our emotions and mental images as well. I also found the comparison between Japanese and English quite enlightening, as it showed how subtle linguistic differences could affect how people describe events and focus on different aspects of a situation. This has implications not only for language learners but also for cross-cultural communication and understanding. It made me appreciate the diversity of human cognition and how learning other languages could expand our perspective on the world. Overall, I believe that understanding how language shapes thought is crucial for fostering empathy and better communication across cultures.
[4] I found this TED Talk really fascinating because it shows how peoples sensitivity and cultural backgrounds can make the same word have different meanings and expressions across languages. Its amazing how language shapes the way we think and perceive the world in unique ways. I was also surprised to learn that there are about 7,000 languages spoken worldwide today. This made me curious about the origins and characteristics of some of the most complex languages, especially Japanese, which is often considered one of the hardest languages to learn. I would love to know more about how Japanese developed and what features make it so challenging compared to other languages. Overall, this talk opened my eyes to the rich diversity of human language and how deeply it connects to culture and cognition. It inspires me to appreciate different languages more and motivates me to learn about them in depth.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                
[5] It was interesting that the Kuuk Thaayorre people use  north, south, east, and west to describe things instead of left and right. I have no sense of direction, so I thought it may be difficult for me to speak with them. Until i watched this video, the way people understand the information is the same in languages such as english, spanish, german and other kinds of countries of europe. However, I learned that it actually is not the same, and I thought the power of languages is very strong. In Japan, we can see the languages disappearing. I thought the young generations need to make changes if we dont want to lose our languages.
